         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1968"/><citedRange>210</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>28, 45</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... should fade completely like fire extinguished by water. 1. The mountain gods, who took note of this, speak in wonder:</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1952"/><citedRange>11-13</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>54, 129</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:kolver1965"/><citedRange>22, 122</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(Oh on) the power (of compassion). || In the D.-tune: || See his compassion towards the murdering hunter, [his] enemy, splitting his heart with a sharp arrow.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2 #a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>187</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Sehet sein Mitleid gegen den mordenden Jäger, [seinen] Feind, [der] mit scharfem Pfeil [sein] Herz durchbohrt. ... [seine] Adern bedrohte förmlich der (Jäger), aber dieser hegte (nicht) böse Gesinnung gegen Ihn.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">Behold his compassion towards the murdering hunter, [his] enemy, [who] with a sharp arrow pierces [his] heart. ... [his] veins the (hunter) virtually threatened, but this one did (not) harbour a bad disposition towards him.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>164</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>222</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1968"/><citedRange>213</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>28</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:kolver1965"/><citedRange>108</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... he [i.e., the hunter] increased as it were the pressure in [his] veins, but this one did (not) harbour any evil disposition towards him. (Because of) trust (the arrow) penetrated [his] body. Because of (?) the Bodhisattva-like ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>87, 200</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>20</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... his spirit should be cheerful. 1. (Thereupon) Subhadrā (again) says to the Bodhisattva: You have spoken well. The Kāṣāya-</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>15</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(robe is praised as the best by all good ones). || In the M.-tune: || By the friendly, the merciful, and by all of the good ones the monk’s robe has of old (?) been praised as the best.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>348f</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>34</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (of such a robe (?), no) fear there is, [just] (like) the (moon)god (brings forth) only coolness (?), not burning. 1. See (, however, oh venerable one), has not from the monk’s robe</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>87</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1958"/><citedRange>299</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>564</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(arisen distress for you?) The Bodhisattva says: Do not plague my spirit [and my] heart again, for in no way [has] distress arisen (for me) from the monk’s robe.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>259</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>125</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... for me. See, oh skilled one, of all evil things passion, wrath [and] ign(orance) are (the source). Certainly this one’s</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>189</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(venomous arrow [is] caused by this). There is (no passion), wrath or ignorance in his heart (with regard to) this matter [pertaining to] myself. (And) therefore he [is] without guilt. He [is] in the power of the three Kleśas.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>55</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1967c"/><citedRange>175</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(Miserable [is]) this (world). || In the N.-tune: || Caused by (the three Kleśas) and by the assistance of the bow the venomous arrow went (into) my</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>354</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(breast) ... Or whatever the hunter’s guilt, the hapless one [is] in the power of the Kleśas. See the guilt of the Kleśas, not the guilt of the man,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>36</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>47</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:kolver1965"/><citedRange>26</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(not the guilt of the robe. Thereupon) Subhadrā, exceedingly irritated, says to [her] husband: I am not able (to bear) your death because of this talk.</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="philcomment">The translation is largely based on <bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1952"/><citedRange>11-13</citedRange></bibl>, and <bibl><title corresp="ref:carlingetal2009"/></bibl>.</note><note type="remarks">This text continues from <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a78"/> and continues on <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a79"/>.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">This line seems to contain the end of a tune of 4x12 syllables, rhythm 5/7, spoken by the Boddhisattva.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">This tune has 20/22/10/15 syllables, rhythm 5/5/5/5 + 8/7/7 + 5/5 + 8/7.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="lingcomment"><bibl><title corresp="ref:couvreur1954b"/><citedRange>260</citedRange></bibl> would prefer to supplement to <hi>kārmets(un)e(yo)</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment">This tune has 4x12 syllables, rhythm 4/4/4.</note><note corresp="#a6" type="lingcomment">For <hi>wpäss</hi> <bibl><title corresp="ref:couvreur1954b"/><citedRange>261</citedRange></bibl> suggests either 'coolness', or the Act. Pt. Sg. 3 of a verbal root <hi>wäp-</hi> (cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegetal1931"/><citedRange>469</citedRange></bibl>).</note><note corresp="#b4" type="lingcomment"><bibl><title corresp="ref:couvreur1954b"/><citedRange>259 f</citedRange></bibl>inds the translation of <hi>añcäl śkaṃ masal (yamtsune-yo)</hi> as “and by the assistance of the bow” hard to accept; a more obvious alternative <hi>(tri kleśā)syo rarätku añcäl</hi> “by the three kleśas the bow [was] prompted (and by its assistance etc.)” is impeded by the feminine gender of <hi>ancäl</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">This tune has 4x15 syllables, rhythm 7/8.</note></p>
